\begin_layout Abstract
SPARQ is an advanced global optimization algorithm,
 the direct evolution of an earlier method called ARQ2.
 It searches efficiently for the best solution to problems where the space of options is too vast to check exhaustively,
 such as tuning antenna arrays or planning fuel-efficient spacecraft trajectories.
 Like its predecessor,
 it works with a population of candidate solutions that improve generation after generation,
 alternating between two complementary search strategies.
 What sets SPARQ apart is that it makes nearly every part of this process adaptive.
 Its population shrinks intelligently as the search matures.
 Its internal settings draw from a memory of many past successful configurations,
 not a single average.
 Its escape-from-stagnation mechanisms come in graduated strength,
 from a gentle nudge to a deeper partial restart.
 It also adds capabilities its predecessor never had,
 including a dedicated phase that locally polishes the current best solution using its own memory of productive directions.
 Every addition is kept only where it has been proven to genuinely help.
 The result is markedly more reliable than its predecessor,
 while staying grounded in the same battle-tested core.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
SPARQ;
 Continuous optimization;
 Evolutionary algorithm;
 Adaptive parameter control;
 Metaheuristics;
 Differential evolution;
 Algorithm benchmarking;
 Population-based search;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimization problems in which the goal is to locate the best possible configuration of a set of continuous variables,
 without relying on gradient information and without any guarantee that the objective function is smooth,
 convex,
 or even continuous,
 arise throughout engineering,
 physics,
 and applied economics.
 Formally,
 such problems are instances of global optimization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\mathbf{x}\in\Omega}f(\mathbf{x}),\qquad\Omega:=[\ell_{1},u_{1}]\times\dots\times[\ell_{D},u_{D}]\subset\mathbb{R}^{D},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Omega\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is accessed only through pointwise evaluations,
 and derivative information may be unavailable.
 Given an evaluation budget 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{fe}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
,
 an algorithm produces a sequence of iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{x}_{t}\}_{t=1}^{N_{fe}}$
\end_inset

 and tracks the best-so-far value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\min}(t):=\min_{1\le s\le t}f(\mathbf{x}_{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task is to locate the global minimum (or maximum) of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 despite the presence of numerous local optima,
 ill-conditioning,
 and,
 in many real applications,
 a strict limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{fe}$
\end_inset

 on how many times the objective function can be evaluated.
 The difficulty of this task grows sharply with the dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

,
 and no single search strategy can be expected to perform best on every possible problem instance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "problem"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In response,
 the optimization literature has developed several broad families of methods.
 Exact and gradient-based methods offer strong convergence guarantees but require differentiability assumptions that most real-world objective functions do not satisfy.
 Classical local random search methods,
 most notably the algorithm of Solis and Wets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SolisAndWets"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 instead perturb a single candidate solution and accept improving moves,
 offering simplicity at the cost of a tendency to stall in local optima.
 To escape this limitation,
 the field turned to population-based metaheuristics,
 which explore the search space with many candidate solutions simultaneously.
 Early and influential examples include simulated annealing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 genetic algorithms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 together with more recent refinements to their initialization strategies such as k-means-based seeding 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GiantArmadillo"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 particle swarm optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PSO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and the Covariance Matrix Adaptation Evolution Strategy (CMA-ES) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CMAES"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 later extended to large-scale problems via limited-memory variants such as LM-CMA-ES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LMCMAES"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More recently,
 a growing number of bio-inspired metaheuristics have been proposed and subsequently refined through hybridization with local search and modern termination criteria,
 as in the case of the Giant-Armadillo Optimization method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "InitialDistribution"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among population-based metaheuristics,
 Differential Evolution (DE),
 introduced by Storn and Price 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and since surveyed extensively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 has proven especially effective and has spawned an active line of successive refinements.
 JADE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "JADE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduced the current-to-pbest mutation strategy together with an external archive of recently displaced solutions,
 both of which became standard components of later variants.
 SHADE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SHADE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 replaced JADE's single adaptive parameter pair with a historical memory of successful settings,
 and L-SHADE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LSHADE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 combined this with a linear population size reduction scheme building on earlier work on population sizing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 jSO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "JSO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 refined this further with progress-dependent parameter schedules,
 and subsequent work introduced rank-based selective pressure in choosing difference vectors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LSHADE2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 culminating in NL-SHADE-RSP 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NL-SHADE-RSP"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which combined non-linear population size reduction with rank-based selection and adaptive archiving.
 A parallel line of research explored hybridizing DE with other search paradigms and enriching its crossover operator:
 CoBiDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CoBiDE"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduced covariance-guided,
 bimodal parameter sampling;
 individual-dependent DE variants (IDE) proposed alternative generation-based scheduling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEp"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 eigenvector-based ("eigen") crossover,
 aligning the crossover operation with the population's natural axes of variation rather than the raw coordinate axes,
 was introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SPS-L-SHADE-EIG"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and later integrated into a cooperative multi-algorithm framework,
 EA4Eig,
 that combines CoBiDE,
 IDE,
 CMA-ES,
 and jSO under a shared eigen-crossover mechanism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "EI4Eig"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Separately,
 other general-purpose mechanisms have been proposed for escaping stagnation and premature convergence,
 including opposition-based learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "obl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "obde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Lévy-flight perturbations based on the numerical simulation method of Mantegna 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mantegna"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and,
 from the domain of sequential decision-making,
 Thompson sampling as a principled method for adaptively allocating trials between competing strategies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Thompson"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method presented in this article,
 SPARQ,
 is the latest member of a family of Differential-Evolution-based optimizers developed internally,
 beginning with ARQ 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ARQ"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and its direct successor ARQ2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ARQ2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 both of which combine a current-to-pbest DE mutation strategy with an alternative individual-dependent evolution strategy (IDE) selected via an adaptive roulette mechanism,
 restricted tournament replacement,
 an external archive,
 and outlier quarantine.
 SPARQ builds directly on ARQ2's architecture while replacing nearly every one of its fixed or singly-adapted mechanisms with an adaptive counterpart drawn from the DE literature surveyed above,
 among them a SHADE-style historical memory in place of a single running parameter average,
 non-linear population size reduction,
 rank-based selective pressure in the style of NL-SHADE-RSP,
 a jSO-style progress-dependent schedule for its elitist pressure,
 eigen-coordinate crossover,
 a Thompson-sampling bandit in place of frequency-based strategy selection,
 and Lévy-flight-based quarantine perturbations.
 On top of this synthesis,
 SPARQ introduces two mechanisms with no counterpart in ARQ2 or the algorithms above:
 a stagnation-gated local polishing phase based on the classical Solis-Wets adaptive random search,
 and a short-term memory of recently successful search directions ("trajectory echo") that is replayed during this local phase.
\end_layout

