\begin_layout Subsection
ARQ:
 A Cohesive Optimization Design with Outlier Quarantine
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ARQ"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ARQ"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a differential-evolution-based optimizer built around a single,
 cohesive update cycle that combines four complementary mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Archive-assisted pbest/1/bin trial generation.
 Each new candidate is generated by attracting a target vector toward one of the top-p fraction of the population,
 plus a difference term drawn partly from the live population and partly from an external archive of recently displaced solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=x+F\,(x_{pbest}-x)+F\,(r_{1}-r_{2}),\qquad r_{1}\in P_{t},\ r_{2}\in P_{t}\cup A_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is followed by binomial crossover and projection back onto the feasible box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Success-history parameter adaptation.
 The scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and crossover rate 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

 are drawn from a Cauchy and a Normal distribution,
 respectively,
 centered on running means 
\begin_inset Formula $μ_{F}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
,
 
\begin_inset Formula $μ_{CR}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
.
 After each cycle,
 these means are updated using gain-weighted statistics,
 a weighted Lehmer mean for F and a weighted arithmetic mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

,
 so that parameter settings that produced larger fitness gains are trusted more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Restricted Tournament Replacement (RTR).
 A trial vector first competes against its own parent,
 if it fails to improve,
 it is instead compared against its nearest neighbor (in bounds-normalized distance) within a small random pool drawn from the population,
 and replaces that neighbor if superior.
 This localizes selection pressure and helps preserve population diversity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outlier quarantine and targeted micro-restart.
 ARQ's central contribution is an event-driven mechanism that detects fitness outliers using a robust interquartile-range threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $θ=Q3+a\cdot IQR$
\end_inset

 and gently relocates a fraction of them toward a robust center (the mean of the best half of the population) under a small perturbation,
 accepting the repair only if it improves fitness.
 A complementary micro-restart,
 triggered after a fixed number of non-improving iterations,
 perturbs a small fraction of the worst individuals around the current incumbent.
 Together,
 these two mechanisms convert destabilizing outliers into controlled exploration stimuli,
 narrowing the gap between best-case and average-case performance without sacrificing peak results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ARQ2:
 A Roulette-Guided Hybrid Extension of ARQ
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ARQ2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ARQ2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 preserves this entire stability-oriented backbone but extends it into an asymmetric hybrid architecture in which two internal search branches,
 ARQ and an auxiliary IDE (Individual-dependent Differential Evolution) branch,
 operate on a shared population and a shared external archive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Roulette-based branch scheduling.
 At each iteration,
 a controller selects which of the two branches to execute,
 based on branch "credits" that are updated in proportion to each branch's recent number of successful replacements.
 Branches with higher recent credit are selected more often,
 but a reset mechanism restores both branches to a common baseline credit whenever either branch's selection probability falls below a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $δ$
\end_inset

,
 preventing one branch from permanently dominating and collapsing the hybrid into a single-strategy method.
 An initial bootstrap phase enforces the ARQ branch for a fixed number of early iterations,
 before branch competition becomes informative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The IDE branch.
 When selected,
 this branch constructs its donor vectors using its own,
 per-individual memories of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

,
 and a progress-dependent elite-guided pool whose size and guidance strength shift over the course of the search,
 favoring stronger elite guidance early on,
 and a more balanced elite/random mixture later.
 It further switches between two donor forms (guidance-based and current-based) depending on a phase threshold that adapts if the branch's success rate stalls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An enriched ARQ branch.
 When the ARQ branch is selected,
 its mutation rule is enriched with a jSO-style,
 progress-dependent attraction coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $K(π)$
\end_inset

 that modulates how strongly each new candidate is pulled toward an elite exemplar,
 growing more elitist as the search progresses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asymmetric stabilization.
 Importantly,
 the quarantine and micro-restart mechanisms inherited from ARQ remain attached only to the ARQ branch.
 This preserves the original design's corrective role without duplicating the same machinery inside the auxiliary IDE branch,
 while still letting IDE contribute a structurally distinct search dynamic that helps on multimodal landscapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirically,
 this hybridization was shown to primarily strengthen repeated-run reliability:
 across 36 benchmark problems,
 ARQ2 improved on ARQ's mean-value performance on 21 problems (matching it on 11,
 and trailing on only 4),
 while remaining highly competitive in best-case terms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ARQ2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Proposed Method:
 SPARQ
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:sparq"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The mechanisms of the SPARQ
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:mechanisms"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SPARQ is built directly on top of ARQ2's architecture (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ARQ2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
 it retains the shared population,
 the shared external archive,
 and the two-branch structure (ARQ vs.
 IDE),
 but it replaces nearly every one of ARQ2's fixed or singly-adapted mechanisms with an adaptive counterpart,
 and adds several mechanisms with no counterpart in ARQ2 at all.
 This section describes each addition in turn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Population State and Non-Linear Population Size Reduction (NLPSR)
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:NLPSR"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike ARQ2,
 which runs with a fixed population size 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 throughout,
 SPARQ starts from an initial size 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{init}$
\end_inset

 (by default scaled with dimension,
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{init}=18D$
\end_inset

) and shrinks it toward a floor 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{min}$
\end_inset

 as the search progresses,
 following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(t)=\text{round}\Big(N_{init}+(N_{min}-N_{init})\cdot p(t)^{,e(t)}\Big),\qquad e(t)=1-(1-\alpha_{\text{NL}})\cdot p(t),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)∈[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of the evaluation budget consumed so far and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{NL}}\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 controls the shape of the reduction:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{NL}}=1$
\end_inset

 recovers a purely linear LSHADE-style schedule,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{NL}}<1$
\end_inset

produces a near-linear reduction early in the search that accelerates as the budget is exhausted,
 in the spirit of NL-SHADE-RSP.
 At the end of every iteration,
 if the current population exceeds the target size,
 the worst individuals are discarded,
 freeing up evaluations for the remaining ones.
 The cached eigenbasis (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:EigenCrossover"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is invalidated whenever the population shrinks,
 since it must be recomputed on the new,
 smaller sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the comparative evaluation reported in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ExperimentalResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 however,
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{init}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 was fixed at 100 for SPARQ and for every other population-based competitor in the comparison,
 overriding the dimension-scaled default 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{init}=18D$
\end_inset

.
 This choice ensures that all compared methods start from an identical population size rather than from method-specific,
 dimension-dependent values,
 so that observed performance differences reflect the search mechanisms themselves rather than differences in initial population sizing.
 The dimension-scaled schedule 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{init}=18D$
\end_inset

 remains SPARQ's default,
 recommended setting outside of this controlled comparison.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
SHADE-Style Historical Memory for F and CR
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:3.2. SHADEStyle"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2 keeps a single,
 continuously-updated pair of running means (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{F},\mu_{CR}$
\end_inset

).
 SPARQ instead maintains a circular memory of size 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(M_{F}^{k},M_{CR}^{k})\}_{k=1}^{H}$
\end_inset

,
 one slot of which (the "terminal" slot,
 following jSO) is permanently pinned to a high value (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{F}^{H}=M_{CR}^{H}=0.9$
\end_inset

) rather than being overwritten.
 Before generating each trial,
 a memory slot 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is drawn uniformly at random,
 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CR\sim\mathcal{N}(M_{CR}^{r},0.1),\qquad F\sim\text{Cauchy}(M_{F}^{r},0.1),
\]

\end_inset

both resampled/clamped to their valid ranges (
\begin_inset Formula $CR∈[0,1]CR\in[0,1]CR∈[0,1],F\in[F_{lo},F_{hi}]$
\end_inset

).
 Two jSO-style schedules further constrain these draws early in the search:
 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

 is floored at 0.7 before 20% progress and at 0.6 before 50% progress,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is capped at 
\begin_inset Formula $0.7+0.3\,p(t)$
\end_inset

 before 60% progress.
 After each generation,
 the (non-terminal) memory slots are updated cyclically using the same gain-weighted Lehmer/arithmetic mean rule as ARQ2,
 but only one slot advances per generation rather than the single running pair,
 so that a diverse set of previously-successful settings remains available for future sampling rather than being collapsed into one blended average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Rank-Based Selective Pressure and jSO-Style Elitism Schedule
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:RankBased"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2 draws the difference-vector companions 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 (and,
 when not drawn from the archive,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

) uniformly at random from the population.
 SPARQ instead biases this choice toward better-ranked individuals:
 given the population sorted by fitness (rank 0 = best),
 an index at rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is selected with probability proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $(N-r)^{k_{r}}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
,
 where the selective-pressure exponent itself increases linearly over the run,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{r}(t)=k_{r,init}+(k_{r,final}-k_{r,init})\cdot p(t),\qquad k_{r,init}=2,\ k_{r,final}=3,
\]

\end_inset

so that rank bias is moderate early on and sharpens later,
 in the style of LSHADE-RSP.
 Independently,
 the size of the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

best pool from which the elite-attraction target 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{pbest}$
\end_inset

 is drawn also narrows over the course of the run,
 following a jSO-style linear schedule from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{max}=0.25$
\end_inset

 down to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{min}=0.10$
\end_inset

,
 so that the elitist pull becomes progressively more selective as the search matures.
 A further NL-SHADE-RSP-style refinement,
 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

-sorting,
 reassigns the sampled 
\begin_inset Formula $CR$
\end_inset

 values within each generation's batch of parents so that better-ranked parents receive the smallest values (conservative,
 fine-grained crossover) and worse-ranked parents the largest (more disruptive recombination).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Eigen-Coordinate Binomial Crossover
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:EigenCrossover"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2's binomial crossover operates coordinate-by-coordinate in the raw problem coordinates,
 which is ill-suited to correlated,
 non-separable landscapes whose productive directions run diagonally across several variables at once.
 SPARQ periodically estimates the dominant axes of the current population's spread:
 using the best 50% of individuals (by fitness),
 it computes their empirical covariance matrix,
 diagonalizes it via Jacobi rotation to obtain an eigenbasis 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and per-axis scale factors,
 and refreshes this basis every 
\begin_inset Formula $\texttt{eig\_period}$
\end_inset

 iterations (or whenever the population is resorted or resized).
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{eig}=0.40$
\end_inset

,
 and whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 stays within a practical cap (
\begin_inset Formula $D\le100$
\end_inset

,
 since the Jacobi decomposition is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(D^{3})$
\end_inset

 per sweep),
 the binomial crossover of Equation (10) in ARQ2's formulation is instead applied in the rotated coordinate system:
 both the parent and the mutant are projected onto the eigenbasis (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e}=B^{\top}x$
\end_inset

),
 crossover is performed there,
 and the result is rotated back (
\begin_inset Formula $u=B\,u_{e}$
\end_inset

).
 This lets the operator recombine along the population's natural axes of variation rather than the arbitrary problem axes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Thompson Sampling Bandit for Strategy Selection
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Thompson"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2 selects between the ARQ and IDE branches using a frequency-based "credit" roulette with a threshold-triggered reset.
 SPARQ replaces this with a genuine two-armed Bayesian bandit:
 each branch 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 maintains a Beta posterior with parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k},b_{k}$
\end_inset

),
 initialized with a mild prior favoring ARQ (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ARQ}=2$
\end_inset

) to provide brief warm-up bias before a short deterministic bootstrap (a small fixed number of forced ARQ iterations) hands control to the bandit.
 At each iteration,
 a sample is drawn from each arm's posterior via two Gamma draws,
 and the arm with the larger sample is selected.
 After a branch executes,
 its posterior is updated in proportion to its observed success rate,
 normalized by the number of trial evaluations actually attempted so that a large IDE sweep and a smaller ARQ sweep are weighted comparably,
 between iterations,
 both posteriors are geometrically decayed toward their uninformative prior (1,1) to accommodate a non-stationary environment,
 in which a strategy that was previously effective may cease to be so as the population and progress evolve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Lévy-Flight Quarantine
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:LévyFlight"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2's quarantine mechanism relocates fitness outliers (detected via the interquartile threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=Q_{3}+\alpha\cdot IQR$
\end_inset

) toward the centroid of the top half of the population using an ordinary Gaussian perturbation.
 SPARQ instead perturbs each repaired outlier using a symmetric Lévy-stable step,
 generated via the Mantegna (1994) algorithm:
 a step 
\begin_inset Formula $u/|v|^{1/\beta}$
\end_inset

 is formed from two correlated Gaussian draws 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.5$
\end_inset

,
 producing a distribution that is mostly small but occasionally very large,
 mimicking the search pattern of animals foraging under scarce resources.
 Applied per coordinate and scaled by the box range,
 this gives quarantined individuals a genuine chance of relocating to a distant,
 unexplored region rather than merely oscillating near the population centroid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
On-Demand Opposition-Based Basin Escape
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ODOBB"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This mechanism has no counterpart in ARQ2.
 It monitors two independent signals:
 the number of consecutive iterations without any improvement in the incumbent best (
\begin_inset Formula $no\_improve\ge stag\_trigger$
\end_inset

),
 and the population's normalized spread (the average,
 per-coordinate,
 box-normalized standard deviation across the population) falling below a small collapse ratio.
 When both conditions hold simultaneously,
 and a cooldown counter has elapsed,
 a fraction of the worst individuals are relocated to points computed as a quasi-opposition of their current position,
 either the exact reflection through the center of the box,
 or a point interpolated between that reflection and the current incumbent best,
 and the relocation is accepted only if it improves fitness.
 This directly targets premature convergence:
 rather than waiting for a general-purpose restart,
 it intervenes as soon as the population has visibly collapsed onto a single region while genuinely failing to progress,
 forcing a look at the opposite side of the search space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Stagnation-Gated Elite Polish
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StagnationPolish"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the most substantial addition with no analogue in ARQ2.
 Whenever the incumbent best has failed to improve by a meaningful relative margin for a number of iterations (this trigger tightens to a single stagnant iteration in the closing quarter of the budget),
 SPARQ enters a short,
 budget-capped burst (never more than a fixed fraction,
 by default 12%,
 of the evaluations consumed so far) of local refinement attempts centered on the current best 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{best}$
\end_inset

.
 Each attempt draws one of four probe modes at random:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Single-coordinate probing (round-robin over dimensions,
 so that every coordinate is eventually visited even in high dimension):
 either a coordinate-wise opposition (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\to\ell_{j}+u_{j}-x_{j}$
\end_inset

) or an adaptive Gaussian perturbation of that one coordinate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Anisotropic eigen-aligned steps,
 drawn as a Gaussian in the (possibly slightly stale) eigenbasis of Section 3.4,
 scaled per-axis by the square root of the corresponding eigenvalue,
 so that steps are long along the population's natural "valley" and short across it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Trajectory echo (described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:TrajectoryEcho"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solis-Wets adaptive random search (described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "SolisWets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 below,
 integrated as the fourth probe mode).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each successful probe (one that improves 
\begin_inset Formula $best_{f}$
\end_inset

) is injected into the population by overwriting its current worst member,
 propagating the refinement into the DE core's own mutation pool,
 probe-mode-specific step sizes are adapted by a 1/5-success rule (grown on success,
 shrunk on failure).
 The whole mechanism is protected by three independent safety nets:
 a hard evaluation-budget cap,
 an exponential cooldown backoff whenever an entire burst fails to find any improvement,
 and an efficiency arbitration that compares the gain-per-evaluation achieved by the polish against the gain-per-evaluation achieved by the ordinary evolutionary loop over the same interval,
 forcing the polish to stand down whenever the core DE search is demonstrably the better investment of evaluations.
 A landscape-level self-selection rule additionally imposes a long cooldown whenever several consecutive bursts produce only negligible relative gains,
 so that the mechanism naturally becomes inactive on landscapes (such as those with a distant global optimum reachable only through large exploratory jumps) where local refinement of the current incumbent is not productive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Trajectory Echo:
 A Memory of Recently Successful Directions
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:TrajectoryEcho"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also with no counterpart in ARQ2:
 whenever the DE core (either the ARQ branch's restricted-tournament acceptance or the IDE branch's greedy replacement) accepts a strictly improving trial,
 the accepted displacement (trial vector minus the individual it replaced) is pushed into a small,
 fixed-size ring buffer of at most eight entries.
 As one of the elite-polish probe modes (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:StagnationPolish"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 a candidate step is formed as a random linear combination of the buffered directions,
 normalized so that its expected magnitude stays comparable to a single one of its ingredients regardless of how many are currently buffered.
 This lets the polish phase replay an echo of movements that have already proven productive during this specific run,
 of particular value on problems where genuine improvement requires shifting several coordinates together in a coordinated way,
 a pattern that isotropic or single-coordinate probing cannot easily discover.
 Like the other probe modes,
 this mechanism carries its own circuit breaker:
 a run of repeated failures disables it for the remainder of the search rather than continuing to spend evaluations on a direction source that has stopped paying off.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Solis-Wets Adaptive Local Search
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "SolisWets"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fourth elite-polish probe mode is a single running trajectory,
 based on the classical adaptive random search method of Solis and Wets (1981),
 anchored at the current incumbent.
 A bias vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (initialized at zero) accumulates a memory of productive directions.
 Each attempt draws a random perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and first tries 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{best}+b+\delta$
\end_inset

;
 if that fails to improve,
 it tries the exact reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{best}-b-\delta$
\end_inset

 using the same random draw before giving up.
 A success in the biased direction grows 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 toward that direction and expands the step scale,
 a success only in the reflected direction shrinks 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and partially reverses it;
 and a failure in both directions decays 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 toward zero and contracts the step,
 the classical Solis-Wets rule for avoiding wasted wandering.
 Because this probe mode only ever evolves a single trajectory from the current incumbent,
 rather than recombining information from two different population members,
 it cannot produce the kind of structurally incoherent points that a population-level recombination operator could produce on permutation-symmetric landscapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hard-Stagnation Rejuvenation
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:HardStagnationRejuvenation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ARQ2's single micro-restart mechanism is replaced in SPARQ by a two-tier system.
 A survival trigger fires whenever the population's fitness spread has collapsed to near-zero (a looser condition than any typical similarity-based stopping rule),
 and re-seeds only a small sliver (about 5%) of the population uniformly at 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:HardStagnationRejuvenation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

random,
 at each iteration if needed;
 its purpose is purely to keep the population from appearing fully converged to an external stopping rule while genuine progress is still possible.
 A hard-stagnation trigger fires only once the incumbent has failed to improve for a much longer interval (a configurable multiple of the basin-escape threshold of Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ODOBB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the population has also collapsed,
 when it fires,
 it re-seeds a much larger fraction of the population (by default,
 all but the top 25%) uniformly at random,
 while explicitly preserving the incumbent best itself,
 which is never part of the population and is therefore never at risk.
 An escalation mechanism further tracks whether repeated firings of either tier keep failing to produce meaningful gains:
 a persistent survival-tier failure forces a hard-stagnation escape early,
 and a persistent hard-stagnation failure escalates to a near-complete reset (keeping only a small safety fraction),
 preventing a strong-but-insufficient partial restart from being immediately "reconquered" by an entrenched elite on unusually deceptive landscapes.
 The SHADE memory of Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:3.2. SHADEStyle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is deliberately preserved rather than reset across a rejuvenation event,
 since it continues to encode useful parameter statistics for the refreshed population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Overall Control Flow
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:OverallControlFlow"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each SPARQ iteration proceeds as follows.
 The archive is trimmed to its capacity;
 a branch (ARQ or IDE) is selected,
 either by the initial bootstrap or by the Thompson bandit of Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Thompson"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 and executed,
 with the ARQ branch additionally followed by Lévy-flight quarantine (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:LévyFlight"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Two independent stagnation counters are then updated,
 one tracking any improvement at all (feeding the basin-escape and rejuvenation triggers),
 and one tracking only meaningful relative improvement (feeding the elite-polish trigger,
 so that large populations at high dimensionality,
 where some individual improves the incumbent by a vanishing amount almost every generation,
 do not starve the polish mechanism of activations).
 The elite polish (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:StagnationPolish"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the basin escape (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ODOBB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 and the rejuvenation mechanism (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:HardStagnationRejuvenation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

