\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:meanRanking1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

reports the corresponding ranking based on mean value.
 This is a stricter criterion,
 since it rewards consistency across repeated runs rather than a single strong result.
 Under this criterion,
 SPARQ ranks first on 20 of 45 problems,
 or 44.4%.
 This is a lower share than the 55.6% obtained under the best-value criterion.
 Its exclusive,
 untied first-place count rises slightly to 6 of 45,
 compared with 7 of 45 for jSO.
 Despite this lower first-place frequency,
 SPARQ's mean rank across the benchmark set is 3.02.
 This is marginally better than EA4Eig at 3.04,
 and it is the best mean rank among all ten methods.
 SPARQ never registers the worst rank,
 10th,
 on any problem.
 The divergence between the best-value and mean-value criteria is most pronounced on rotatedrosenbrock.
 There,
 SPARQ's rank worsens from 5th to 8th.
 On tersoffc it worsens from 7th to 8th.
 On potential,
 by contrast,
 it improves from 2nd to 1st.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Results on Large-Scale,
 High-Dimensional Benchmark Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subsection presents the outcome of the comparative evaluation on the large-scale portion of the benchmark suite.
 SPARQ is compared against five optimizers developed specifically for high-dimensional search:
 CCDG2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CCDG2_1,CCDG2_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 LM-CMA-ES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LMCMAES"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 MMES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MMES"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 RMES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RMES"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and VkD-CMA-ES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VkD-CMA-ESc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The comparison covers seventeen benchmark problems,
 each evaluated at two dimensions,
 d = 1000 and d = 10,000,
 for a total of thirty-four problem-dimension combinations.
 The problem set spans separable functions of low intrinsic difficulty alongside strongly non-separable and multimodal landscapes,
 allowing both the accuracy and the computational scalability of each method to be assessed as the number of variables grows by an order of magnitude.
 As in the previous subsection,
 every method was executed independently over a fixed number of repeated runs under an identical evaluation budget.
 Three complementary tables report the results.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:comparison2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents detailed statistics for each method and problem-dimension combination,
 namely the best value found,
 the mean value,
 the success rate,
 the standard deviation,
 and the execution time.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:bestRankin2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports the ranking of all six methods according to the best value achieved,
 and Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:meanRanking2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports the corresponding ranking according to the mean value.
\end_layout

